Desmodium gyroides

    Authority   (Roxb.)
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Rosidae:Fabales:Leguminosae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 5261

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION: An erect, often much branshed, woody shrub 1-2.5 or
   4 m in height. Old stems can reach 4 cm in diameter. Leaves with 1ˆ3
   oval leaflets (up to 8 cm long and 5 cm wide) on petioles 1ˆ3 cm long.
   Flower colour starts light pink and then becomes darker. Seedpods up to
   5 cm long. USE: Leaves are used as a high protein forage and as green
   manure. It is used as shade in coffee and cacao plantations and being
   tested for contour hedges. It is mentioned as a possible agroforestry
   species. GROWING PERIOD: Short-lived perennial. It can persist through
   a dry season of up to 3 months but is not productive under drought
   conditions. COMMON NAMES: Karikut-ritkut, Koer. FURTHER INF: Scientific
   synonym: Codariocalyx gyroides, Hedysarum gyroides, Meibomia gyroides.
   Karikut-ritkut is native of South and Southeast Asia. It can be grown
   up to 2000 m in the tropics or in the subtropical lowlands. It can
   tolerate short-term flooding. Tolerant of low fertility, high Al, low
   pH and poor drainage and can be grown in a range of soil. It is
   nitrogen fixing.

   Sources
   [10]Grassland Index
   Hensleigh T 1988 pp 142-145 [LIG, FER, DEP, PH, DRA, TEMP, RAIN, USE]
   Tropical forages 2005

